				<td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=56464&amp;sid=eb75c655baeed3a196bec49c62e93420#56464"><img src="templates/myth2/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Wed Nov 24, 2004 11:33 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject:                                                             </span></td>
				<td valign="top" align="right" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=56464&amp;sid=eb75c655baeed3a196bec49c62e93420"><img src="templates/myth2/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Nvidia cards seem to do better with OpenGL games (Doom3 ect..), and ATI cards seem to do better with DX9 games (Halflife2). The difference though is not that much.  I have an ATI 9500Pro 128mb card, it does fine with EQ (but was supprised on the lack of a performance boost when upgrading from a Geforce 3 Ti/200 64mb card), but I do get what seems like an ATI induced crash every once and a while. The wifes Geforce FX 5200 128mb card never seems to have a problem (but it doesn't have ME F'ing around with it all the time either. Don't underestimate user induced crashes, as much as I hate to say it...lol). A good card with 128mb ram is better than a bad (slower) card with 256mb ram. BTW, a Geforce 6800GT did not improve my EQ experience over the 9500Pro. But EQ seems not to care what card you have, and long as it supports DX9.
<br />

<br />
Raid will only benifit you on disk intensive tasks like installing windows (15 minute install -vs- over an hour without) or loading zones. My zone times in EQ went from about 30-35 seconds with a single ATA133 5400 rpm drive to about 12 seconds with two SATA 150 10k rpm drives (Raid0). Raid will do nothing for framerates.
<br />

<br />
On ram, the difference between the PC2700 and PC3200 ram is clock rate. The 2700 operates at 166 mhz, and the 3200 operates at 200 mhz (before factoring in the DDR stuff).
<br />

<br />
As far as CPUs go, I run a Pentium4 2.4 ghz cpu, and the wife has an Athlon XP1800+. Both with 1 gig of DDR ram (hers is PC2100, mine PC3200). They run EQ about the same, mine is a little smoother. But if I fire up  3dMark 2001SE, her box beats mine. Not sure why.
<br />

<br />
Thats my buck-three-fiddy worth.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=410691" target="_blank" class="postlink"><span style="color: fusha">Iumien Soulchamber</span> </a> 
<br />
Arch Lich
